#X text 35 383 Nonetheless \, most the term "phase inversion" is used
as a \, misnomer \, by suggesting we're actually talking about ap hase
shift when in fact we're talking abouut polarity inversion \, which
is actually neither a time shift nor a phase shift!;
#X text 35 439 Yes \, this is very confusing and needs a lot of attention!
This is why the term "polarity inversion" is preffered and used in
this tutorial \, but you'll see many audio gear reffering to a phase
shift of 180 degrees \, when what it is doing is actually just a polarity
inversion., f 60;
#X text 35 520 Note that both phase and polarity inversion give the
same result for a sine wave because of its waveform \, in which the
second half of its cycle is symmetric and with the sign inverted. Other
common waveforms with this characteristic are the triangular and regular
square waves (with a pulse width of 0.5).;
#X text 735 31 Sawtooth waveforms do not have this characteristic.
Hence \, a phase opposition is not the same as inverting the polarity.
